# What is rsync Command?

    -> The rsync command in Linux is a powerful utility used for:

        => File transfer
        => File synchronization
        => Backup operations
        => Directory mirroring

    -> rsync stands for remote synchronization. It efficiently copies files between:

        => Local directories
        => Remote systems
        => Servers over a network

**** The command rsync uses SSH command by default.

    -> Verify to see if rsync is installed or not;

        # rsync --version

        # which rsync or 
        
        # command -v rsync

    -> How to install rsync;

        # apt install rsync

        # dnf install rsync

    -> Archive mode:

        # rsync -a source/ destination/

        -> Archive mode preserves:

            => Permissions
            => Ownership
            => Timestamps
            => Symbolic links

    -> Verbose mode:

        # rsync -av source/ destination/

**** When specifying a directory;

        dir1 -> Will copy the entire directory

        dir1/ -> copies the content of the directory.

    -> Copying a directory & its content: (-r -> recursive option)

        # rsync -rv <source-dir> <destination-dir>

    -> Dry run mode (test run): (use this method to check if everything is correct)

        # rsync --dry-run dir1 dir100/ 

    -> Display progress mode:

        # rsync -avp source/ destination/ //Option p is used to display the progress. Most suitable when copying large files.

    -> Backup files in a local system:

        # rsync -avp --delete <source-path> <destination-path> //Command will copy incremental files and delete non-exiting files from the destination.

        Example:

            # rsync -avp --delete play-ground Backups/

    -> Backup files to a remote system:

        # rsync -avp --delete <source-path> <destination-path(remote-system)>

        Example:

            # rsync -avp --delete play-ground iwbandara@192.168.1.105:/home/iwbandara/backups/

    -> How to copy files/directory content from a remote system:

        # rsync -rv username@ip-address:<source-path> <destination-path>

        Example:

            # rsync -rv iwbandara@192.168.10.10:backups/ notes/ //Copies content in the directory

            # rsync -rv iwbandara@192.168.10.10:backups notes/ //Copies entire 'backups' directory

    -> How to compress file when moving:

        # rsync -zva <source> <destination> //Content will be compressed while transfer happens.

    -> How to remove the source files when moving:

        # rsync -rva --remove-source-files <source> <destination> //Source files (only) will be removed from the source location. No directories will be removed.        

**** The graphical application is called grsync.

    # apt install grsync

